{"slug": "wand", "root": "wand", "category": "item", "gloss": "a rod/virga directing power", "definition": "A wand is a rod that directs magical power — a slender staff or twig the magician holds to point, command, and channel. It contrasts with vessels and effigies: not a thing that contains or represents, but an instrument of the gesture itself, the extension of the caster's will along a line.", "history": "From Old Norse *vöndr*, 'a supple rod, switch' (Proto-Germanic *wanduz*, from a root meaning 'to wind') — the magician's wand is, at bottom, a whippy twig you could bend; Latin's rival word *virga* gives us 'verge.' The instrument is as old as the literature: the wand is the standard accessory of the classical magician, first attested in the *Odyssey*, where Circe strikes her victims with her *rhabdos*. Ritual manuals kept it central — the operator's hazel wand among his swords and censer — down to the ceremonial magic of the grimoires and beyond.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Page & Rider, The Routledge History of Medieval Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Klaassen, The Transformations of Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. wand (Old Norse vöndr)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Old Norse", "origin": "Old Norse vöndr 'a supple rod, switch' (Proto-Germanic *wanduz, root 'to wind')", "first": "c. 1300", "note": "The magician's wand is, by origin, a whippy twig you could bend. Latin's rival word virga gives us 'verge'.", "hook": "The magic wand was just a bendy stick."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 4, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 3, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 14, "by_variant": {"wand": 2, "wands": 2}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"C":